Thus we may say, “Socrates is man, animal, &c.” Second intentions are not so predicable: we cannot say, ‘⁶ Socrates is species, genus, &c.” Hence when we are told that a predicable is commune, univocum, secundae intentionis, it is not meant that all universale are in themselves second intentions; but that every predicate vien-ed in relation to its subject may be comprehended under one of Porphyry's five classes of pre- dicables; all which are second intentions.
